# Platform Profile: Cursor

**Provider:** Anysphere  
**Interface:** AI-native IDE (VS Code fork), web, mobile, Slack  
**Core identity:** A full IDE — not a plugin, not a chat interface

---

## Strengths
- Full codebase context — indexes entire repo with custom embeddings; agents recall across massive codebases
- Agent Mode: autonomous multi-file editing, test running, and validation
- Background Agents: cloud-based agents run autonomously while you work locally; produce merge-ready PRs
- Multi-model: runs Claude, GPT, Gemini, and Grok — select per task
- Parallel agents: up to 8 agents running simultaneously on discrete subtasks
- Composer mode: multi-file refactoring with diff preview before applying
- MCP integrations: Figma, Linear, GitHub, Stripe, Amplitude, AWS and more
- SKILL.md and .cursor/rules: persistent configuration files read automatically
- Used by 30,000+ NVIDIA developers; 20–40% delivery speed gains reported
- Cursor Blame (Enterprise): tracks which lines are AI-generated vs human-written

## Weaknesses
- Not suited for tasks outside a codebase (research, document production, strategy)
- Credit-based billing: heavy model usage depletes credits faster
- Requires internet — no offline mode
- AI output is a first draft; still requires human review and judgment
- Learning curve for rule/skill configuration to get consistent agent behavior

## Context Window
- Depends on model selected: Claude 200K, GPT-5 1M, Gemini 2M available
- Codebase indexing supplements context — agents don't need to paste files manually
- Behavior: strongest codebase-aware context of any IDE platform

## Memory & Persistence
- **SKILL.md:** Procedural "how-to" instructions, invoked via slash commands
- **.cursor/rules:** Directory of always-on rule files applied automatically by agents
- **RULE.md:** File-specific or project-level rules
- **CLAUDE.md:** Respected when present (common in open source projects)
- **Handoff note:** Always update `.cursor/rules` or add a SKILL.md before a handoff session — this is how Cursor retains configuration across sessions

## System Prompt Support
- ✅ Via `.cursor/rules` and SKILL.md (always-on and invocable)
- ✅ Via system prompt in Agent mode
- Configuration files are the primary persistence surface — more reliable than chat context

## Tool Availability
- Full filesystem read/write (project-scoped)
- Shell command execution
- Git operations (diff, commit, branch, PR creation)
- Test execution
- Package manager access
- Web browser (Agent mode)
- MCP integrations (marketplace + custom)
- Cloud agent sandboxes (Background Agents)

## Prompt Format Conventions
- Task prompts: specific, file-referenced, with acceptance criteria
- Reference files by path: `src/components/Card.jsx` not "the card component"
- SKILL.md files: procedural step-by-step instructions — Cursor treats them like runbooks
- .cursor/rules: concise, declarative rules — one concern per rule file
- Agent mode: describe the outcome, not just the steps — agents plan execution
- Composer: describe the change; Cursor shows the diff before applying

## Ideal Task Types
- Multi-file refactoring (the primary Cursor differentiator)
- Architecture changes across a large repo
- Test suite generation and coverage improvement
- Codebase onboarding (new engineer understanding an unfamiliar repo)
- DevOps and Infrastructure as Code
- Autonomous PR generation (Background Agents)
- Any task where "the AI should just do it in the actual files" is the goal

